Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper deals with the propagation processes of signals received by a typical user, which involves information theory concepts such as signal-to-interference-plus-noise ratio (SINR) and link layer performance. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper discusses heterogeneous cellular networks and their comparison, which falls under the domain of networking and internet architecture. 
3. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks): The paper may have applications in social networks, as cellular networks are a form of social network where users communicate with each other through base stations. 
4. cs.MA (Multiagent Systems): The paper may have implications for multiagent systems, as cellular networks involve multiple agents (base stations) interacting with each other and with users. 
5. cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory): The paper may have connections to game theory, as cellular networks involve strategic decisions by base stations and users to optimize their performance.
